## Model Definition

```javascript
const { DataTypes } = require('sequelize');

const User = sequelize.define('User', {
  name: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING,
    allowNull: false
  },
  email: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING,
    allowNull: false,
    unique: true
  },
  age: DataTypes.INTEGER
});
```

Sequelize will automatically add `id`, `createdAt`, `updatedAt` fields.

## Sync with Database

```javascript
(async () => {
  await sequelize.sync({ force: true }); // drops and re-creates tables â€“ use with caution!
  console.log('Database synced');
})();
```

In production, use migrations instead of `force: true`.

## Create
```javascript
const user = await User.create({ name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com', age: 30 });
```

## Read
```javascript
const users = await User.findAll();
const user = await User.findOne({ where: { email: 'alice@example.com' } });
const userById = await User.findByPk(1);
```

## Update
```javascript
await User.update({ age: 31 }, { where: { email: 'alice@example.com' } });
// or
const user = await User.findByPk(1);
user.age = 31;
await user.save();
```

## Delete
```javascript
await User.destroy({ where: { email: 'alice@example.com' } });
```
